{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493311"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:04:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:04:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1280"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1280"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.6,0.01,0.08,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1280"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105547"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1280"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1280"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87969"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"125"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1472"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31959"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33095"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38384"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105547"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a seven day history of lower back pain which has worsened in the last two days and is now affecting her sleep. The pain not been responsive to regular paracetamol. Her bladder and bowel function are intact. She has been able to mobilise without difficulty and denies any sensory disturbances. Her medical history includes rheumatoid arthritis, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, and hypertension. Her regular long-term medications include prednisolone, tiotropium, fluticasone/eformoterol, and perindopril/indapamide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysical examination is normal apart from some localised tenderness over the mid-lumbar spine.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No further investigation required","Spine X-ray","Spine ultrasound","Spine CT","Spine MRI"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPatients presenting with back pain is a very common scenario for many medical practitioners especially in general practice. In recent years, evidence has shifted away from ordering initial imaging to investigate acute lower back pain of \u0026lt; 4 weeks in duration without red flags as most cases of lower back pain are mechanical and will improve with time. Imaging showing degenerative changes (which are not the cause of the pain) paradoxically have a negative impact on clinical improvement. Therefore it is very important to triage for red flags in the assessment of lower back pain and determine need for imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has several red flags for back pain requiring imaging including age \u0026gt;40, night pain and being on long term prednisolone which is a risk factor for fragility fractures, therefore she warrants further imaging. First-line imaging will be a \u003Cstrong\u003Espine X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E which can show obvious bony pathology e.g. osteoporotic crush fractures, spondylosis. If there is ongoing clinical concern (eg for tumour) a CT spine can be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional red flags for back pain include: \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAge \u0026lt;20 or \u0026gt;55 years with new onset back pain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHistory of cancer\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnexplained weight loss\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFever or signs of systemic illness\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImmunosuppression, including HIV or use of immunosuppressive medications\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntravenous drug use\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecent significant trauma, or minor trauma in older age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProlonged use of corticosteroids\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESevere unremitting night pain, especially if not relieved by rest\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStructural deformity of the spine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESignificant neurological deficit, including:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProgressive motor weakness\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESaddle anaesthesia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENew onset bladder or bowel dysfunction (possible cauda equina syndrome)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese red flags should prompt further investigation to exclude serious spinal pathology such as malignancy, infection, fracture, or cauda equina syndrome, as recommended by RACGP guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A plain X-ray of the spine should be the initial imaging for most cases of back pain and should only be undertaken if red flags are present."],"references":["Wheeler LP, Karran EL, Harvie DS. Low back pain: Can we mitigate the inadvertent psycho-behavioural harms of spinal imaging?. Australian journal of general practice. 2018. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/september/low-back-pain","Parr A, Askin G. Non-radicular low back pain: Assessment and evidence-based treatment. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2020 Nov;49(11):724. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/november/non-radicular-low-back-pain"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87969"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1280"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87969"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-09T20:43:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-09T20:44:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1280"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105547"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand 